# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: modula-2
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] A separate language, *Sequential Pascal*, is used as the language for applications programs run by the operating systems written in Concurrent Pascal.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Both languages are extensions of Niklaus Wirth's Pascal, and share a common threaded code interpreter.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] The following describes how Concurrent Pascal differs from Wirth's Pascal.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] These omissions make it possible to guarantee, by a combination of compile-time checks and minimal run-time checking in the threaded-code interpreter, that a program can not damage itself or another program by addressing outside its allotted space.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Concurrent Pascal includes class, monitor, and process data types.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Instances of these types are declared as variables, and initialized in an `init` statement.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Classes and monitors are similar: both package private variables and procedures with public procedures (called procedure entries).
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] A class instance can be used by only one process, whereas a monitor instance may be shared by processes.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Monitors provide the only mechanism for interprocess communication in a Concurrent Pascal program.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Only one process can execute within a given monitor instance at a time.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] A built in data type, the queue, together with operations `delay` and `continue`, are used for scheduling within monitors.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Each variable of type queue can hold one process.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] If many processes are to be delayed in a monitor, multiple queue variables, usually organized as an array, must be provided.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] The single process queue variable gives a monitor full control over medium-term scheduling, but the programmer is responsible for unblocking the correct process.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] A process, like a class or monitor, has local variables, procedures, and an initial statement, but has no procedure entries.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] The initial statement ordinarily executes forever, calling local procedures, class procedures, and monitor procedures.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Processes communicate through monitor procedures.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] Language rules prevent deadlock by imposing a hierarchy on monitors.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] But nothing can prevent a monitor from erroneously forgetting to unblock a delayed process (by not calling continue) so the system can still effectively hang up through programming errors.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] The configuration of processes, monitors, and classes in a Concurrent Pascal program is normally established at the start of execution, and is not changed thereafter.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] The communication paths between these components are established by variables passed in the `init` statements, since class and monitor instance variables cannot be used as procedure parameters.
[src:modula-2/concurrent-pascal] The following example shows the declaration of a simple monitor, and its use by two communicating processes.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Wirth viewed Modula-2 as a successor to his earlier programming languages Pascal and Modula.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The language design was influenced by the Mesa language and the Xerox Alto, both from Xerox PARC, that Wirth saw during his 1976 sabbatical year there.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The computer magazine *Byte* devoted the August 1984 issue to the language and its surrounding environment.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Wirth created the Oberon series of languages as the successor to Modula-2, while others (particularly at Digital Equipment Corporation and Acorn Computers, later Olivetti) developed Modula-2 into Modula-2+ and later Modula-3.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Modula-2 is a general purpose procedural language suitable for both systems programming and applications programming.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The syntax is based on Wirth's earlier language, Pascal, with some elements and syntactic ambiguities removed.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The *module* concept, designed to support separate compilation and data abstraction; and direct language support for multiprogramming were added.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The language allows the use of one-pass compilers.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Such a compiler by Gutknecht and Wirth was about four times faster than earlier multi-pass compilers.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] A Modula-2 *module* may be used to encapsulate a set of related subprograms and data structures, and restrict their visibility from other parts of the program.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Except for standard identifiers, no object from the outside is visible inside a module unless explicitly imported; no internal module object is visible from the outside unless explicitly exported.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Then the objects a, b, c, and P from module M1 are known outside module M1 as M1.a, M1.b, M1.c, and M1.P.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] They are exported in a *qualified* manner to the outside (assuming module M1 is global).
[src:modula-2/modula-2] M1, is used as a qualifier followed by the object's name.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Then this means that the objects exported by module M1 to the outside of its enclosing program can now be used inside module M2.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] They are referenced in a *qualified* manner: M1.a, M1.b, M1.c, and M1.P.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] For example, if another module M3 exports an object called P, then the two objects can be distinguished since M1.P differs from M3.P.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] It does not matter that both objects are called P inside their exporting modules M1 and M3.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] This means that objects exported by module M1 to the outside can again be used inside module M4, but now by mere references to the exported identifiers in an *unqualified* manner as: a, b, c, and P.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] This method of import is usable if there are no name clashes.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] It allows variables and other objects to be used outside their exporting module in the same *unqualified* manner as inside the exporting module.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The export and import rules not only safeguard objects against unwanted access, but also allow a cross-reference of the definition of every identifier in a program to be created.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] This property helps with the maintenance of large programs containing many modules.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The language provides for single-processor concurrency (monitors, coroutines and explicit transfer of control) and for hardware access (absolute addresses, bit manipulation, and interrupts).
[src:modula-2/modula-2] There are two major dialects of Modula-2.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The first is *PIM*, named for the book *Programming in Modula-2* by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] There were three major editions of PIM: the second, third (corrected), and fourth.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Each describes slight variants of the language.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The second major dialect is *ISO*, named for the standardization effort by the International Organization for Standardization.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Here are a few of the differences among them.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] There are several derivative languages that resemble Modula-2 very closely but are new languages in their own right.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Many other current programming languages have adopted features of Modula-2.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Modula-2 is used to program many embedded systems.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Cambridge Modula-2 by Cambridge Microprocessor Systems is based on a subset of PIM4 with language extensions for embedded development.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The compiler runs on MS-DOS and it generates code for Motorola 68000 series (M68k) based embedded microcontrollers running a MINOS operating system.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Mod51 by Mandeno Granville Electronics is based on ISO Modula-2 with language extensions for embedded development following IEC 1131, an industry standard for programmable logic controllers (PLC) closely related to Modula-2.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The Mod51 compiler generates standalone code for 80C51 based microcontrollers.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Delco Electronics, then a subsidiary of GM Hughes Electronics, developed a version of Modula-2 for embedded control systems starting in 1985.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] It was the first high-level programming language used to replace machine code (language) for embedded systems in Delco's *engine control units* (ECUs).
[src:modula-2/modula-2] This was significant because Delco was producing over 28,000 ECUs per day in 1988 for GM.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] This was then the world's largest producer of ECUs.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The first production use of Modula-GM was its use in GM trucks starting with the 1990 model year *vehicle control module* (VCM) used to manage GM Powertrain's Vortec engines.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Modula-GM was also used on all ECUs for GM's 90° Buick V6 engine family 3800 Series II used in the 1997-2005 model year Buick Park Avenue.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The Modula-GM compilers and associated software management tools were sourced by Delco from Intermetrics.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Modula-2 was selected as the basis for Delco's high level language because of its many strengths over other alternative language choices in 1986.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] After Delco Electronics was spun off from GM (with other component divisions) to form Delphi Automotive Systems in 1995, global sourcing required that a non-proprietary high-level software language be used.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] ECU embedded software now developed at Delphi is compiled with commercial compilers for the language C.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The satellites of the Russian radionavigation-satellite service framework GLONASS, similar to the United States Global Positioning System (GPS), are programmed in Modula-2.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Turbo Modula-2 was a compiler and an integrated development environment for MS-DOS developed, but not published, by Borland.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Jensen and Partners, which included Borland cofounder Niels Jensen, bought the unreleased codebase and turned it into TopSpeed Modula-2.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] It was eventually sold to Clarion, now SoftVelocity, who then offered the Modula-2 compiler as part of its Clarion product line at that time.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] A Zilog Z80 CP/M version of Turbo Modula-2 was briefly marketed by Echelon under license from Borland.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] A companion release for Hitachi HD64180 was sold by Micromint as a development tool for their SB-180 single-board computer.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] IBM had a Modula-2 compiler for internal use which ran on both OS/2 and AIX, and had first class support in IBM's E2 editor.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] IBM Modula-2 was used for parts of the OS/400 *Vertical Licensed Internal Code* (effectively the kernel of OS/400).
[src:modula-2/modula-2] This code was mostly replaced with C++ when OS/400 was ported to the IBM RS64 processor family, although some remains in modern releases of the operating system.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] A Motorola 68000 backend also existed, which may have been used in embedded systems products.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] Modula-2 is used to program some operating systems (OSs).
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The Modula-2 module structure and support are used directly in two related OSs.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The OS named *Medos-2*, for the Lilith workstation, was developed at ETH Zurich, by Svend Erik Knudsen with advice from Wirth.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] It is a single user, object-oriented operating system built from Modula-2 modules.
[src:modula-2/modula-2] The OS named *Excelsior*, for the Kronos workstation, was developed by the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, Siberian branch, Novosibirsk Computing Center, Modular Asynchronous Developable Systems (MARS) project, Kronos Research Group (KRG).
[src:modula-2/modula-2] It is a single user system based on Modula-2 modules.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] A module interface expresses the elements that are provided and required by the module.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The elements defined in the interface are detectable by other modules.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The implementation contains the working code that corresponds to the elements declared in the interface.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modular programming, in the form of subsystems (particularly for I/O) and software libraries, dates to early software systems, where it was used for code reuse.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modular programming per se, with a goal of modularity, developed in the late 1960s and 1970s, as a larger-scale analog of the concept of structured programming (1960s).
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The term "modular programming" dates at least to the National Symposium on Modular Programming, organized at the Information and Systems Institute in July 1968 by Larry Constantine; other key concepts were information hiding (1972) and separation of concerns (SoC, 1974).
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modules were not included in the original specification for ALGOL 68 (1968), but were included as extensions in early implementations, ALGOL 68-R (1970) and ALGOL 68C (1970), and later formalized.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] One of the first languages designed from the start for modular programming was the short-lived Modula (1975), by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Another early modular language was Mesa (1970s), by Xerox PARC, and Wirth drew on Mesa as well as the original Modula in its successor, Modula-2 (1978), which influenced later languages, particularly through its successor, Modula-3 (1980s).
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modula's use of dot-qualified names, like `M.a` to refer to object `a` from module `M`, coincides with notation to access a field of a record (and similarly for attributes or methods of objects), and is now widespread, seen in C++, C#, Dart, Go, Java, OCaml, and Python, among others.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modular programming became widespread from the 1980s: the original Pascal language (1970) did not include modules, but later versions, notably UCSD Pascal (1978) and Turbo Pascal (1983) included them in the form of "units", as did the Pascal-influenced Ada (1980).
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The Extended Pascal ISO 10206:1990 standard kept closer to Modula2 in its modular support.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Standard ML (1984) has one of the most complete module systems, including functors (parameterized modules) to map between modules.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] In the 1980s and 1990s, modular programming was overshadowed by and often conflated with object-oriented programming, particularly due to the popularity of C++ and Java.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] For example, the C family of languages had support for objects and classes in C++ (originally C with Classes, 1980) and Objective-C (1983), only supporting modules 30 years or more later.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Java (1995) supports modules in the form of packages, though the primary unit of code organization is a class.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] However, Python (1991) prominently used both modules and objects from the start, using modules as the primary unit of code organization and "packages" as a larger-scale unit.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Perl 5 (1994) also includes support for both modules and objects, with a vast array of modules being available from CPAN (1993).
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] OCaml (1996) followed ML by supporting modules and functors.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modular programming is now widespread, and found in virtually all major languages developed since the 1990s.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The relative importance of modules varies between languages, and in class-based object-oriented languages there is still overlap and confusion with classes as a unit of organization and encapsulation, but these are both well-established as distinct concepts.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The term *assembly* (as in .NET languages like C#, F#, or Visual Basic) or *package* (as in Dart, Go, or Java) is sometimes used instead of *module*.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] In other implementations, these are distinct concepts; in Python a package is a set of modules, while in Java 9 the introduction of the Java Platform Module System, in which a new module concept, involving a set of packages with enhanced access control, was implemented.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] In Java, the term *package* is used for the module concept in the Java language specification.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The *module*, a kind of set of a package, was introduced in Java 9.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] In some Pascal dialects, the term *unit* is used for the module concept.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] A component is a similar concept, but typically refers to a higher level; a component is a piece of a whole system, while a module is a piece of an individual program.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] The scale of the term "module" varies significantly between languages; in Python it is very small-scale and each file is a module, while in Java 9 it is large-scale, where a module is a set of packages, which are in turn sets of files.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Conspicuous examples of languages that lack support for modules are C, and in their original forms, C++ and Pascal.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] C and C++ do, however, allow separate compilation and declarative interfaces to be specified using header files which is commonly considered modularization.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modules were added to Objective-C in iOS 7 (2013), and to C++ with C++20.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Pascal was superseded by Modula and Oberon, which included modules from the start, and various derivatives that included modules.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] JavaScript has had native modules since ECMAScript 2015.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] C++ modules have allowed backwards compatibility with headers (with "header units").
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Dialects of C allow for modules, for example Clang supports modules for the C language, though the syntax and semantics of Clang C modules differ from C++ modules.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Modular programming can be performed even where the programming language lacks explicit syntactic features to support named modules, like, for example, in C.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] This is done by using existing language features, together with, for example, coding conventions, programming idioms and the physical code structure.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] IBM i also uses modules when programming in the Integrated Language Environment (ILE).
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] With modular programming, concerns are separated such that modules perform logically discrete functions, interacting through well-defined interfaces.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Often modules form a directed acyclic graph (DAG); in this case a cyclic dependency between modules is seen as indicating that these should be a single module.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] In the case where modules do form a DAG they can be arranged as a hierarchy, where the lowest-level modules are independent, depending on no other modules, and higher-level modules depend on lower-level ones.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] A particular program or library is a top-level module of its own hierarchy, but can in turn be seen as a lower-level module of a higher-level program, library, or system.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] When creating a modular system, instead of creating a monolithic application (where the smallest component is the whole), several smaller modules are written separately so when they are composed together, they construct the executable application program.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Typically, these are also compiled separately, via separate compilation, and then linked by a linker.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] A just-in-time compiler may perform some of this construction "on-the-fly" at run time.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] These independent functions are commonly classified as either program control functions or specific task functions.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Program control functions are designed to work for one program.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Specific task functions are closely prepared to be applicable for various programs.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] This makes modular designed systems, if built correctly, far more reusable than a traditional monolithic design, since all (or many) of these modules may then be reused (without change) in other projects.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] This also facilitates the "breaking down" of projects into several smaller projects.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] Theoretically, a modularized software project will be more easily assembled by large teams, since no team members are creating the whole system, or even need to know about the system as a whole.
[src:modula-2/modular-programming] They can focus just on the assigned smaller task.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] Niklaus Emil Wirth was born in Winterthur, Switzerland, on 15 February 1934.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] He was the son of Hedwig (née Keller) and Walter Wirth, a high school teacher.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] Wirth studied electronic engineering at the Federal Institute of Technology, Zürich (ETH Zürich) from 1954 to 1958, graduating with a Bachelor of Science (B.S.) degree.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1960, he earned a Master of Science (M.Sc.) from Université Laval in Quebec.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] Then in 1963, he was awarded a PhD in electrical engineering and computer science (EECS) from the University of California, Berkeley, supervised by computer design pioneer Harry Huskey.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] From 1963 to 1967, Wirth served as assistant professor of computer science at Stanford University and again at the University of Zürich.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1968, he became a professor of informatics at ETH Zürich, taking two one-year sabbaticals at Xerox PARC in California (1976–1977 and 1984–1985).
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] He was also a major part of the design and implementation team for the operating systems Medos-2 (1983, for the Lilith workstation) and Oberon (1987, for the Ceres workstation), and for the Lola (1995) digital hardware design and simulation system.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1984, Wirth received the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) Turing Award for the development of these languages.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1994, he was inducted as a Fellow of the ACM.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1999, he received the ACM SIGSOFT Outstanding Research Award.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1995, he popularized the adage now named Wirth's law.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] The April 1971 *Communications of the ACM* article "Program Development by Stepwise Refinement", concerning the teaching of programming, is considered to be a classic text in software engineering.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] The paper is considered to be the earliest work to formally outline the top-down method for designing programs.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] The article was discussed by Fred Brooks in his influential book *The Mythical Man-Month* and was described as "seminal" in the ACM's brief biography of Wirth published in connection to his Turing Award.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] The 1973 textbook *Systematic Programming: An Introduction* was described as a quality source for mathematicians desiring to understand the nature of programming in a 1974 review.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1974, *The Pascal User Manual and Report*, jointly written with Kathleen Jensen, served as the basis of many language implementation efforts in the 1970s (BSD Pascal), and 1980s in the United States and across Europe.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1975, he wrote the book *Algorithms + Data Structures = Programs*, which gained wide recognition.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] Major revisions of this book with the new title *Algorithms & Data Structures* were published in 1986 and 2004.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] The examples in the first edition were written in Pascal.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] These were replaced in the later editions with examples written in Modula-2 and Oberon, respectively.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] In 1992, Wirth and Jürg Gutknecht published the full documentation of the Oberon operating system.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] A second book, with Martin Reiser, was intended as a programming guide.
[src:modula-2/niklaus-wirth] Wirth died in Zürich on New Year's Day 2024, at age 89.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal was developed on the pattern of the ALGOL 60 language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Wirth was involved in the process to improve the language as part of the ALGOL X efforts and proposed a version named ALGOL W.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This was not accepted, and the ALGOL X process bogged down.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 1968, Wirth decided to abandon the ALGOL X process and further improve ALGOL W, releasing this as Pascal in 1970.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] On top of ALGOL's scalars and arrays, Pascal enables defining complex data types and building dynamic and recursive data structures such as lists, trees and graphs.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal has strong typing on all objects, which means that one type of data cannot be converted to or interpreted as another without explicit conversions.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Unlike C (and also unlike most other languages in the C family), Pascal allows nested procedure definitions to any depth, and allows most kinds of definitions and declarations inside subroutines (procedures and functions).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A program is thus syntactically similar to a single procedure or function.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This is similar to the block structure of ALGOL 60, but restricted from arbitrary block statements to just procedures and functions.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal became very successful in the 1970s, notably on the burgeoning minicomputer market.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Compilers were also available for many microcomputers as the field emerged in the late 1970s.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was widely used as a teaching language in university-level programming courses in the 1980s, and also used in production settings for writing commercial software during the same period.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was displaced by the C programming language during the late 1980s and early 1990s as UNIX-based systems became popular, and especially with the release of C++.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A derivative named Object Pascal designed for object-oriented programming was developed in 1985.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This was used by Apple Computer (for the Lisa and Macintosh machines) and Borland in the late 1980s and later developed into Delphi on the Microsoft Windows platform.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Extensions to the Pascal concepts led to the languages Modula-2 and Oberon, both developed by Wirth.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Much of the history of computer language design during the 1960s can be traced to the ALGOL 60 language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] ALGOL was developed during the 1950s with the explicit goal of being able to clearly describe algorithms.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It included a number of features for structured programming that remain common in languages to this day.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Shortly after its introduction, in 1962, Wirth began working on his dissertation with Helmut Weber on the Euler programming language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Euler was based on ALGOL's syntax and many concepts but was not a derivative.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Its primary goal was to add dynamic lists and types, allowing it to be used in roles similar to Lisp.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] By this time, a number of problems in ALGOL had been identified, notably the lack of a standardized string system.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The group tasked with maintaining the language had begun the ALGOL X process to identify improvements, calling for submissions.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Wirth and Tony Hoare submitted a conservative set of modifications to add strings and clean up some of the syntax.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] These were considered too minor to be worth using as the new standard ALGOL, so Wirth wrote a compiler for the language, which became named ALGOL W.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The ALGOL X efforts would go on to choose a much more complex language, ALGOL 68.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The complexity of this language led to considerable difficulty producing high-performance compilers, and it was not widely used in the industry.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This left an opening for newer languages.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal was influenced by the ALGOL W efforts, with the explicit goals of teaching programming in a structured fashion and for the development of system software.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A generation of students used Pascal as an introductory language in undergraduate courses.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Other goals included providing a reliable and efficient tool for writing large programs, and bridging the canyon between scientific and commercial programming, as represented by the then-widespread languages Fortran and COBOL, with a general-purpose language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] One of the early successes for the language was the introduction of University of California, San Diego's (UCSD) UCSD Pascal, a version that ran on a custom operating system that could be ported to different platforms.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A key platform was the Apple II, where it saw widespread use as Apple Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This led to Pascal becoming the primary high-level language used for development in the Apple Lisa, and later, the Macintosh.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Parts of the original Macintosh operating system were hand-translated into Motorola 68000 assembly language from the Pascal source code.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The typesetting system TeX by Donald Knuth was written in WEB, the original literate programming system, based on Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Successful commercial applications like Adobe Photoshop were written in Macintosh Programmer's Workshop Pascal, while applications like Total Commander, Skype and Macromedia Captivate were written in Delphi (Object Pascal).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Apollo Computer used Pascal as the systems programming language for its operating systems beginning in 1980.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Variants of Pascal have also been used for everything from research projects to PC games and embedded systems.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Newer Pascal compilers exist which are widely used.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Wirth's example compiler meant to propagate the language, the Pascal-P system, used a subset of the language designed to be the minimal subset of the language that could compile itself.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The idea was that this could allow bootstrapping the compiler, which would then be extended to full Pascal language status.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This was done with several compilers, but one notable exception was UCSD Pascal, which was based on Pascal-P2.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It kept the subset status of the language based on the idea that this would run better on the new (then) microprocessors with limited memory.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] UCSD also converted the Pascal-P2 interpreter into a "byte machine", again, because it would be a better fit for byte-oriented microprocessors.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal formed the basis of many systems, including Apple Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Borland Pascal was not based on the UCSD codebase, but arrived during the popular period of UCSD and matched many of its features.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This started the line that ended with Delphi Pascal and the compatible Open Source compiler FPC/Lazarus.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The ISO standard for Pascal, ISO 7185, was published in 1983 and was widely implemented and used on mainframes, minicomputers and IBM-PCs and compatibles from 16 bits to 32 bits.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The two dialects of Pascal most in use towards the end of the 20th century and up until today are the ISO 7185 standard version and the Delphi/Turbo Pascal versions (of which the two Borland versions are mostly compatible with each other).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] During work on the Lisa, Larry Tesler began corresponding with Wirth on the idea of adding object-oriented extensions to the language, to make Pascal a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This led initially to Clascal, introduced in 1983.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] As the Lisa program faded and was replaced by the Macintosh, a further version was created and named Object Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This was introduced on the Mac in 1985 as part of the MacApp application framework, and became Apple's main development language into the early 1990s.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The Object Pascal extensions were added to Turbo Pascal with the release of version 5.5 in 1989.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Over the years, Object Pascal became the basis of the Delphi system for Microsoft Windows, which is still used for developing Windows applications, and can cross-compile code to other systems.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Free Pascal is an open source, cross-platform alternative with its own graphical integrated development environment (IDE) named Lazarus.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The first Pascal compiler was designed in Zürich for the CDC 6000 series mainframe computer family.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Niklaus Wirth reports that a first attempt to implement it in FORTRAN 66 in 1969 was unsuccessful due to FORTRAN 66's inadequacy to express complex data structures.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The second attempt was implemented in a C-like language (Scallop by Max Engeli) and then translated by hand (by R.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Schild) to Pascal itself for boot-strapping.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Many Pascal compilers since have been similarly self-hosting, that is, the compiler is itself written in Pascal, and the compiler is usually capable of recompiling itself when new features are added to the language, or when the compiler is to be ported to a new environment.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The GNU Pascal compiler is one notable exception, being written in C.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The first successful port of the CDC Pascal compiler to another mainframe was completed by Welsh and Quinn at the Queen's University of Belfast (QUB) in 1972.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The target was the International Computers Limited (ICL) 1900 series.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This compiler, in turn, was the parent of the Pascal compiler for the Information Computer Systems (ICS) Multum minicomputer.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The Multum port was developed – with a view to using Pascal as a systems programming language – by Findlay, Cupples, Cavouras and Davis, working at the Department of Computing Science in Glasgow University.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It is thought that Multum Pascal, which was completed in the summer of 1973, may have been the first 16-bit implementation.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A completely new compiler was completed by Welsh et al. at QUB in 1977.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It offered a source-language diagnostic feature (incorporating profiling, tracing and type-aware formatted postmortem dumps) that was implemented by Findlay and Watt at Glasgow University.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This implementation was ported in 1980 to the ICL 2900 series by a team based at Southampton University and Glasgow University.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The Standard Pascal Model Implementation was also based on this compiler, having been adapted, by Welsh and Hay at Manchester University in 1984, to check rigorously for conformity to the BSI 6192/ISO 7185 Standard and to generate code for a portable abstract machine.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The first Pascal compiler written in North America was constructed at the University of Illinois under Donald B.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Gillies for the PDP-11 and generated native machine code.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Microsoft had Pascal compilers for IBM PCs; see Microsoft Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The P-system compilers were named Pascal-P1, Pascal-P2, Pascal-P3, and Pascal-P4.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P1 was the first version, and Pascal-P4 was the last to come from Zürich.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The version termed Pascal-P1 was coined after the fact for the many different sources for Pascal-P that existed.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The compiler was redesigned to enhance portability, and issued as Pascal-P2.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This code was later enhanced to become Pascal-P3, with an intermediate code backward compatible with Pascal-P2, and Pascal-P4, which was not backward compatible.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The Pascal-P4 compiler–interpreter can still be run and compiled on systems compatible with original Pascal (as can Pascal-P2).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] However, it only accepts a subset of the Pascal language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P5, created outside the Zürich group, accepts the full Pascal language and includes ISO 7185 compatibility.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P6 is a follow-on to Pascal-P5 that, along with other features, aims to be a compiler for specific CPUs, including AMD64.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal branched off Pascal-P2, where Kenneth Bowles used it to create the interpretive UCSD p-System.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was one of three operating systems available at the launch of the original IBM Personal Computer.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal used an intermediate code based on byte values, and thus was one of the earliest *bytecode compilers*.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Apple Pascal was released in 1979 for the Apple II and Apple III computer systems.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was an implementation of, or largely based on, UCSD Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P1 through Pascal-P4 were not, but rather based on the CDC 6600 60-bit word length.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A compiler based on the Pascal-P4 compiler, which created native binary object files, was released for the IBM System/370 mainframe computer by the Australian Atomic Energy Commission; it was named the *AAEC Pascal 8000 Compiler* after the abbreviation of the name of the commission.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Apple Computer created its own Lisa Pascal for the Lisa Workshop in 1982, and ported the compiler to the Apple Macintosh and MPW in 1985.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 1985 Larry Tesler, in consultation with Niklaus Wirth, defined Object Pascal and these extensions were incorporated in both the Lisa Pascal and Mac Pascal compilers.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In the 1980s, Anders Hejlsberg wrote the Blue Label Pascal compiler for the Nascom-2.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A reimplementation of this compiler for the IBM PC was marketed under the names Compas Pascal and PolyPascal before it was acquired by Borland and renamed *Turbo Pascal*.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Turbo Pascal became hugely popular, thanks to an aggressive pricing strategy, having one of the first full-screen IDEs, and very fast turnaround time (just seconds to compile, link, and run).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was written and highly optimized entirely in assembly language, making it smaller and faster than much of the competition.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 1986, Anders ported Turbo Pascal to the Macintosh and incorporated Apple's Object Pascal extensions into Turbo Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] These extensions were then added back into the PC version of Turbo Pascal for version 5.5.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] At the same time Microsoft also implemented the Object Pascal compiler.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Turbo Pascal 5.5 had a large influence on the Pascal community, which began concentrating mainly on the IBM PC in the late 1980s.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Many PC hobbyists in search of a structured replacement for BASIC used this product.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It also began to be adopted by professional developers.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Around the same time a number of concepts were imported from C to let Pascal programmers use the C-based application programming interface (API) of Microsoft Windows directly.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] These extensions included null-terminated strings, pointer arithmetic, function pointers, an address-of operator, and unsafe typecasts.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Turbo Pascal and other derivatives with *unit* or *module* structures are modular programming languages.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] However, it does not provide a nested module concept or qualified import and export of specific symbols.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Super Pascal adds non-numeric labels, a return statement and expressions as names of types.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] TMT Pascal was the first Borland-compatible compiler for 32-bit MS-DOS compatible protected mode, OS/2, and Win32.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It extends the language with function and operator overloading.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The universities of Wisconsin–Madison, Zürich, Karlsruhe, and Wuppertal developed the *Pascal-SC* and *Pascal-XSC* (*Extensions for Scientific Computation*) compilers, aimed at programming numerical computations.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Development for Pascal-SC started in 1978 supporting ISO 7185 Pascal level 0, but level 2 support was added at a later stage.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-SC originally targeted the Z80 processor, but was later rewritten for DOS (x86) and 68000.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-XSC has at various times been ported to Unix (Linux, SunOS, HP-UX, AIX) and Microsoft/IBM (DOS with EMX, OS/2, Windows) operating systems.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It operates by generating intermediate C source code which is then compiled to a native executable.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Some of the Pascal-SC language extensions have been adopted by GNU Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal Sol was designed around 1983 by a French team to implement a Unix-like system named Sol.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was standard Pascal level-1 (with parameterized array bounds) but the definition allowed alternative keywords and predefined identifiers in French and the language included a few extensions to ease system programming (e.g. an equivalent to lseek).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The Sol team later on moved to the ChorusOS project to design a distributed operating system.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] IP Pascal is an implementation of the Pascal programming language using Micropolis DOS, but was moved rapidly to CP/M-80 running on the Z80.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It was moved to the 80386 machine types in 1994, and exists today as Windows XP and Linux implementations.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 2008, the system was brought up to a new level and the resulting language termed "Pascaline" (after Pascal's calculator).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It includes objects, namespace controls, dynamic arrays, and many other extensions, and generally features the same functionality and type protection as C#.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It is the only such implementation that is also compatible with the original Pascal implementation, which is standardized as ISO 7185.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal, in its original form, is a purely procedural language and includes the traditional array of ALGOL-like control structures with reserved words such as `if`, `then`, `else`, `while`, `for`, and `case`, ranging on a single statement or a `begin`-`end` statements block.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal also has data structuring constructs not included in the original ALGOL 60 types, like records, variants, pointers, enumerations, and sets and procedure pointers.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Such constructs were in part inherited or inspired from Simula 67, ALGOL 68, Niklaus Wirth's own ALGOL W and suggestions by C.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal programs start with the `program` keyword with a list of external file descriptors as parameters (not required in Turbo Pascal etc.); then follows the main block bracketed by the `begin` and `end` keywords.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Semicolons separate statements, and the full stop (i.e., a period) ends the whole program (or *unit*).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Letter case is ignored in Pascal source.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A type declaration in Pascal is used to define a range of values which a variable of that type is capable of storing.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It also defines a set of operations that are permissible to be performed on variables of that type.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The range of values allowed for the basic types (except Boolean) is implementation defined.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Functions are provided for some data conversions.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] For conversion of `real` to `integer`, the following functions are available: `round` (using rounding half away from zero) and `trunc` (rounds towards zero).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Often-used types like byte and string are already defined in many implementations.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Normally the system will use a word to store the data.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] For instance, the `byte` type may be stored in a machine integer—32 bits perhaps—rather than an 8-bit value.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal does not contain language elements that allow the basic storage types to be defined more granularly.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This capability was included in a number of Pascal extensions and follow-on languages, while others, like Modula-2, expanded the built-in set to cover most machine data types like 16-bit integers.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The `packed` keyword tells the compiler to use the most efficient method of storage for the structured data types: sets, arrays and records, rather than using one word for each element.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Packing may slow access on machines that do not offer easy access to parts of a word.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A set is a fundamental concept for modern mathematics, and they may be used in many algorithms.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Such a feature is useful and may be faster than an equivalent construct in a language that does not support sets.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] For these examples, which involve sets over small domains, the improved performance is usually achieved by the compiler representing set variables as bit vectors.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The set operators can then be implemented efficiently as bitwise machine code operations.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A record is a structure comprising any number of member elements called fields.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Fields are defined by specifying an identifier–data type pair delimited by a colon; nested records are possible.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The field list is then terminated by the `end` keyword.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A record variable's fields can later be accessed by inserting a dot (`.`) between the record name and the field identifiers.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A record may also consist of *variants*, which are constants defined by a parenthesized list of field declarations.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A `case ... of` clause is used at the end of the record to declare the *variable part*, containing the number of variants of the type specified within the clause.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Variant records allow several fields of the record to overlap each other to save memory.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] As shown in the example above, Pascal files are sequences of components.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Every file has a buffer variable which is denoted by *f^*.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The procedures *get* (for reading) and *put* (for writing) move the buffer variable to the next element.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Read is introduced such that *read(f, x)* is the same as *x := f^; get(f);*.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Write is introduced such that *write(f, x)* is the same as *f^ := x; put(f);* The type `text` is predefined as file of char.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Here the variable *NodePtr* is a pointer to the data type *Node*, a record.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pointers to not-yet-defined types can be declared (in the above example, pNode is a pointer to a Node, but Node is not yet defined when the pointer type is defined).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This is a forward declaration, an exception to the rule that things must be declared before they are used.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Inside of the scope of the *with* statement, a and b refer to the subfields of the record pointer *NodePtr* and not to the record Node or the pointer type pNode.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Linked lists, stacks and queues can be created by including a pointer type field (c) in the record.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Unlike many languages that feature pointers, Pascal only allows pointers to reference dynamically created variables that are anonymous, and does not allow them to reference standard static or local variables.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pointers also must have an associated type, and a pointer to one type is not compatible with a pointer to another type (e.g. a pointer to a char is not compatible with a pointer to an integer).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This helps eliminate the type security issues inherent with other pointer implementations, particularly those used for PL/I or C.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Some of these restrictions can be lifted in newer dialects.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal is a structured programming language, meaning that the flow of control is structured into standard statements, usually without "goto" commands.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal structures programs into procedures and functions.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Generally, a procedure is used for its side effects, whereas a function is used for its return value.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Procedures and functions can be nested to any depth, and the "program" construct is the logical outermost block.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] By default, parameters are passed by value.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] If "var" precedes a parameter's name, it is passed by reference.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Each procedure or function can have its own declarations of goto labels, constants, types, variables, and other procedures and functions, which must all be in that order.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This ordering requirement was originally intended to allow efficient single-pass compilation.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] However, in some dialects (such as Delphi) the strict ordering requirement of declaration sections has been relaxed.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal adopted many language syntax features from the ALGOL language, including the use of a semicolon as a statement separator.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This is in contrast to other languages, such as PL/I and C, which use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] No semicolon is needed before the `end` keyword of a record type declaration, a block, or a *case* statement; before the `until` keyword of a repeat statement; and before the `else` keyword of an *if* statement.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The presence of an extra semicolon was not permitted in early versions of Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] However, the addition of ALGOL-like empty statements in the 1973 *Revised Report* and later changes to the language in ISO 7185:1983 now allow for optional semicolons in most of these cases.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] A semicolon is still not permitted immediately before the `else` keyword in an *if* statement, because the `else` follows a single statement, not a statement sequence.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In nested ifs, a semicolon cannot be used to avoid the dangling else problem (where the inner if does not have an else, but the outer if does) by putatively terminating the nested if with a semicolon – this instead terminates both if clauses.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Instead, an explicit `begin`...`end` block must be used.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 1983, the language was standardized in the international standard IEC/ISO 7185 and several local country-specific standards, including the American ANSI/IEEE770X3.97-1983, and ISO 7185:1983.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] These two standards differed only in that the ISO standard included a "level 1" extension for conformant arrays (an array where the boundaries of the array are not known until run time), where ANSI did not allow for this extension to the original (Wirth version) language.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 1989, ISO 7185 was revised (ISO 7185:1990) to correct various errors and ambiguities found in the original document.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The ISO 7185 was stated to be a clarification of Wirth's 1974 language as detailed by the User Manual and Report [Jensen and Wirth], but was also notable for adding "Conformant Array Parameters" as a level 1 to the standard, level 0 being Pascal without conformant arrays.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This addition was made at the request of C.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Hoare, and with the approval of Niklaus Wirth.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The precipitating cause was that Hoare wanted to create a Pascal version of the (NAG) Numerical Algorithms Library, which had originally been written in FORTRAN, and found that it was not possible to do so without an extension that would allow array parameters of varying size.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Similar considerations motivated the inclusion in ISO 7185 of the facility to specify the parameter types of procedural and functional parameters.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Niklaus Wirth himself referred to the 1974 language as "the Standard", for example, to differentiate it from the machine specific features of the CDC 6000 compiler.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This language was documented in *The Pascal Report*, the second part of the "Pascal users manual and report".
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] On the large machines (mainframes and minicomputers) Pascal originated on, the standards were generally followed.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] On IBM PCs, the Borland standards Turbo Pascal and Delphi have the greatest number of users.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Thus, it is typically important to understand whether a particular implementation corresponds to the original Pascal language, or a Borland dialect of it.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The IBM PC versions of the language began to differ with the advent of UCSD Pascal, an interpreted implementation that featured several extensions to the language, along with several omissions and changes.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Many UCSD language features survive today, including in Borland's dialect.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In 1990, an extended Pascal standard was created as ISO/IEC 10206, which is identical in technical content to IEEE/ANSI 770X3.160-1989 As of 2019, support of Extended Pascal in FreePascal Compiler is planned.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The key feature of Extended Pascal is Modularity and Separate Compilation.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Extended Pascal Application source code files can be separated into one "program file" and multiple "module files".
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Each module file has their own type, constant, variable and procedure/function definitions and programmers can change the order of these "entity definition" areas.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Also, there are some module-specific definition areas called "initialization" areas with the statement `to begin do ...` and "finalization" areas with the statement `to end do ...`, which can manage the initial state and memory allocation of entities inside the module.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] By inserting `import ...` statements between module/program declaration and definition areas, modules can share their own entities with other modules (and programs).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Other major features include variable binding, collections of similar types (Schemata), comprehensive string facilities, complex number type support, `otherwise` keyword for default branch flow in `case` statement, and short circuit boolean evaluation.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Niklaus Wirth's Zürich version of Pascal was issued outside ETH in two basic forms: the CDC 6000 compiler source, and a porting kit called Pascal-P system.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The Pascal-P compiler left out several features of the full language that were not required to bootstrap the compiler.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] For example, procedures and functions used as parameters, undiscriminated variant records, packing, dispose, interprocedural gotos and other features of the full compiler were omitted.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal, under Professor Kenneth Bowles, was based on the Pascal-P2 kit, and consequently shared several of the Pascal-P language restrictions.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal was later adopted as Apple Pascal, and continued through several versions there.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Although UCSD Pascal expanded the subset Pascal in the Pascal-P kit by adding back standard Pascal constructs, it was still not a complete standard installation of Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In the early 1990s, Alan Burns and Geoff Davies developed Pascal-FC, an extension to Pl/0 (from Niklaus' book *Algorithms + Data Structures = Programs*).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Several constructs were added to use Pascal-FC as a teaching tool for Concurrent Programming (such as semaphores, monitors, channels, remote-invocation and resources).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] To be able to demonstrate concurrency, the compiler output (a kind of P-code) could then be executed on a virtual machine.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This virtual machine not only simulated a normal – fair – environment, but could also simulate extreme conditions (unfair mode).
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Borland's Turbo Pascal, written by Anders Hejlsberg, was written in assembly language independent of UCSD and the Zürich compilers.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] However, it adopted much of the same subset and extensions as the UCSD compiler.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This is probably because the UCSD system was the most common Pascal system suitable for developing applications on the resource-limited microprocessor systems available at that time.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Pascal generated a wide variety of responses in the computing community, both critical and complimentary.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Wirth's initial definition of the language was widely criticized.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In particular, Nico Habermann commented in his "Critical Comments on the Programming Language Pascal" (1973) that many of its constructs were poorly defined, in particular for data types, ranges, structures, and goto.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Later, Brian Kernighan, who popularized the C language, outlined his criticisms of Pascal in 1981 in his article "Why Pascal is Not My Favorite Programming Language".
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] The most serious problem Kernighan described was that array sizes and string lengths were part of the type, so it was not possible to write a function that would accept variable-length arrays or even strings as parameters.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] This made it unfeasible to write, for example, a sorting library.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Kernighan also criticized the unpredictable order of evaluation of Boolean expressions, poor library support, and lack of static variables, and raised a number of smaller issues.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Also, he stated that the language did not provide any simple constructs to "escape" (knowingly and forcibly ignore) restrictions and limitations.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Another difficulty was that, like ALGOL 60, the language did not allow procedures or functions passed as parameters to predefine the expected type of their parameters.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] In the two decades after 1975, Pascal gained increasing attention and became a major programming language for important platforms (including Apple II, Apple III, Apple Lisa, Commodore systems, Z-80-based machines and IBM PC) due to the availability of UCSD Pascal and Turbo Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Despite initial criticisms, Pascal continued to evolve, and most of Kernighan's points do not apply to versions of the language which were enhanced to be suitable for commercial product development, such as Borland's Turbo Pascal.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] As Kernighan predicted in his article, most of the extensions to fix these issues were incompatible from compiler to compiler.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Since the early 1990s, however, most of the varieties seem condensed into two categories: ISO and Borland-like.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Extended Pascal addresses many of these early criticisms.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] It supports variable-length strings, variable initialization, separate compilation, short-circuit Boolean operators, and default (`otherwise`) clauses for case statements.
[src:modula-2/pascal-programming-language] Some of the problems arising from the differences in the implementations of Pascal were later partly solved by the advent of Free Pascal, which supports several dialects with mode directives.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Originally, the central goal of the structured programming movement was to eliminate the need for and use of the goto statement.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] As goto provides powerful and flexible flow control, it can be used to write any arbitrarily complex algorithm, but the resulting code often has significant quality issues, commonly described as spaghetti code.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Structured programming replaces goto with constructs that tend to result in better code.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The paradigm became popular and for the most part achieved the goal of supplanting goto.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In fact, its ubiquity is so thorough that for much of software development, it is simply the way code is written, no longer a topic of discussion as it once was.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Structured programming is sometimes associated with modular programming even though they are different.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In a general sense, *structured* implies a sense of modularity and of being written to be efficient and easy to understand and modify, but this is not what structured programming means in a narrow sense.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] After structured programming became popular, the style of programming that preceded it was retroactively called non-structured programming.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Although technically a programming paradigm, it differs from other paradigms in that it was not intentionally designed.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] It was simply the state-of-the-art before structured programming was envisioned.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The paradigm emerged in the late 1950s with the appearance of the ALGOL 58 and ALGOL 60 programming languages, with the latter including support for block structures.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Dijkstra, who coined the term *structured programming*.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The structured program theorem provides the theoretical basis of structured programming.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] It states that three ways of combining programs—sequencing, selection, and iteration—are sufficient to express any computable function.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] This observation did not originate with the structured programming movement; these structures are sufficient to describe the instruction cycle of a central processing unit, as well as the operation of a Turing machine.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Therefore, a processor is always executing a "structured program" in this sense, even if the instructions it reads from memory are not part of a structured program.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] However, authors usually credit the result to a 1966 paper by Böhm and Jacopini, possibly because Dijkstra cited this paper himself.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The structured program theorem does not address how to write and analyze a usefully structured program.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] These issues were addressed during the late 1960s and early 1970s, with major contributions by Dijkstra, Robert W.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Floyd, Tony Hoare, Ole-Johan Dahl, and David Gries.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Donald Knuth accepted the principle that programs must be written with provability in mind, but he disagreed with abolishing the GOTO statement, and as of 2018 has continued to use it in his programs.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In his 1974 paper, "Structured Programming with Goto Statements", he gave examples where he believed that a direct jump leads to clearer and more efficient code without sacrificing provability.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Knuth proposed a looser structural constraint: It should be possible to draw a program's flow chart with all forward branches on the left, all backward branches on the right, and no branches crossing each other.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Some of those knowledgeable in compilers and graph theory have advocated allowing only reducible flow graphs.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Structured programming theorists gained a major ally in the 1970s after IBM researcher Harlan Mills applied his interpretation of structured programming theory to the development of an indexing system for *The New York Times* research file.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The project was a great engineering success, and managers at other companies cited it in support of adopting structured programming, although Dijkstra criticized the ways that Mills's interpretation differed from the published work.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] As late as 1987, it was still possible to raise the question of structured programming in a computer science journal.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Frank Rubin did so in that year with an open letter titled "'GOTO Considered Harmful' Considered Harmful".
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Multiple objections followed, including a response from Dijkstra that sharply criticized both Rubin and the concessions other writers made when responding to him.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] By the end of the 20th century, nearly all computer scientists were convinced that it is useful to learn and apply the concepts of structured programming.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] High-level programming languages that originally lacked programming structures, such as FORTRAN, COBOL, and BASIC, now have them.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Ordered statements executed in sequence.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Although not part of the structured program theorem, languages generally include a block concept that groups a sequence of code so that it acts much like a single statement.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] A language includes a way to mark a sequence of statements as a block that, unless it contains flow control, will be executed sequentially, top-to-bottom.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Some blocks use different syntax for each structure.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] A block (which can be a single statement) is executed depending on the state of the program.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The conditional statement should have at least one true-condition path, and each condition path should have just one exit point.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] (a.k.a. repetition) A block (which can be a single statement) is executed repeatedly until the program reaches a certain state.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Although structured programming limits the flow to have exactly one entry point and exactly one exit point, most languages allow for multiple, early exit.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Generally, a language is intended to support one or more programming paradigms.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] At the same time, even though a language is not intended to support a paradigm, it often can be used in that way regardless.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In theory, any language can be used for structured programming.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] While the use of goto has largely been replaced by structured constructs, most languages provide features that are not strictly consistent with the structured programming theorem.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Most languages provide a return statement that allows for multiple, early return exit points from a function.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] As a function is a block, this feature is counter to the single exit point described in the theorem.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Many languages provide for early exit from a block (other than via return).
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] For example, a loop construct may support a break statement that exits the loop block before its end.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] As the theorem describes, such early-exit logic can be eliminated by adding branches or tests, but this can add significant complexity.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] C is an early and prominent example of these constructs.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Some newer languages also have "labeled breaks", which allow breaking out of more than just the innermost loop.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The need for multiple exits can arise for a variety of reasons, most often either that the function has no more work to do (if returning a value, it has completed the calculation), or has encountered "exceptional" circumstances that prevent it from continuing, hence needing exception handling.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] A problem with early exit is that cleanup statements might not be executed.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] For example, allocated memory is not deallocated, or open files are not closed, causing memory leak and resource leak.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Cleanup must be done at each return site, which is brittle and can easily result in bugs.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] For instance, in later development, a return statement could be overlooked by a developer, and an action that should be performed at the end of a function (e.g., a trace statement) might not be performed in all cases.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Languages without a return statement, such as Pascal, Lisp, and OCaml, do not have this problem.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Most modern languages provide language-level support to prevent such leaks (see resource management).
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] As a structured alternative to using goto and a cleanup block, unwind protection ensures that certain code is runs when execution exits a block; it is often implemented in connection with exception handling as a try-finally.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] An alternative approach, in C++, is resource acquisition is initialization, which uses normal stack unwinding (variable deallocation) at function exit to call destructors on local variables to deallocate resources.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Kent Beck, Martin Fowler, and co-authors have argued in their refactoring books that nested conditionals may be harder to understand than a certain type of flatter structure using multiple exits predicated by guard clauses.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Their 2009 book flatly states that "one exit point is really not a useful rule.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Clarity is the key principle: If the method is clearer with one exit point, use one exit point; otherwise don’t".
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Herb Sutter and Andrei Alexandrescu also argue in their 2004 C++ tips book that the single exit point is an obsolete requirement.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In his 2004 textbook, David Watt writes that "single-entry multi-exit control flows are often desirable".
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Using Tennent's framework notion of sequencer, Watt uniformly describes the control flow constructs found in contemporary programming languages and attempts to explain why certain types of sequencers are preferable to others in the context of multi-exit control flows.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Watt writes that unrestricted gotos (jump sequencers) are bad because the destination of the jump is not self-explanatory to the reader of a program until the reader finds and examines the actual label or address that is the target of the jump.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In contrast, Watt argues that the conceptual intent of a return sequencer is clear from its own context, without having to examine its destination.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Watt writes that a class of sequencers known as *escape sequencers*, defined as a "sequencer that terminates execution of a textually enclosing command or procedure", encompasses both breaks from loops (including multi-level breaks) and return statements.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Watt also examines how exception sequencers differ from escape and jump sequencers; this is explained in the next section of this article.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] In contrast to the above, Bertrand Meyer wrote in his 2009 textbook that instructions like break and continue "are just the old goto in sheep's clothing" and strongly advised against their use.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] He notes that solutions that wrap exceptions for the sake of creating a single exit have higher nesting depth and thus are more difficult to comprehend, and even accuses those who propose to apply such solutions to programming languages that support exceptions of engaging in cargo-cult thinking.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] For example, a program might contain several calls to read files, but the action to perform when a file is not found depends on the meaning (purpose) of the file in question to the program and thus a handling routine for this abnormal situation cannot be located in low-level system code.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Based on these arguments, Watt concludes that jump sequencers or escape sequencers (discussed in the previous section) are not as suitable as a dedicated exception sequencer with the semantics discussed above.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The textbook by Louden and Lambert emphasizes that exception handling differs from structured programming constructs like while loops because the transfer of control "is set up at a different point in the program than that where the actual transfer takes place.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Citing multiple prior studies by others (1999–2004) and their own results, Westley Weimer and George Necula wrote that a significant problem with exceptions is that they "create hidden control-flow paths that are difficult for programmers to reason about".
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] The necessity to limit code to single-exit points appears in some contemporary programming environments focused on parallel computing, such as OpenMP.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Relatively rarely, functions allow multiple *entry.* This is most commonly only *re*-entry into a coroutine (or generator/semicoroutine), where a function yields control (and possibly a value), but can then be resumed where it left off.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] There are a number of common uses of such programming, notably for streams (particularly input/output), state machines, and concurrency.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] From a code-execution point of view, yielding from a coroutine is closer to structured programming than returning from a function, as the function has not actually terminated, and will continue when called again – it is not an early exit.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] However, coroutines mean that multiple functions have execution state – rather than a single call stack of functions – and thus introduce a different form of complexity.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] It is rare for functions to allow entry to an arbitrary position in the function, as in this case the program state (such as variable values) is uninitialized or ambiguous, and this is similar to a goto.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Some programs, particularly parsers and communications protocols, have a number of states that follow each other in a way that is not easily reduced to the basic structures, and some programmers implement the state-changes with a jump to the new state.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] This type of state-switching is often used in the Linux kernel.
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] However, it is possible to structure these systems by making each state-change a separate function and using a variable to indicate the active state (see trampoline).
[src:modula-2/structured-programming] Alternatively, these can be implemented via coroutines, which dispense with the trampoline.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] WSN has been used in several international standards, starting with ISO 10303-21.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] It was also used to define the syntax of EXPRESS, the data modelling language of STEP.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] The element on the left is defined to be the combination of elements on the right.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] A production is terminated by a full stop (period).
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] We take these concepts for granted today, but they were novel and even controversial in 1977.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] Wirth later incorporated some of the concepts (with a different syntax and notation) into extended Backus–Naur form.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] Notice that `letter` and `character` are left undefined.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] If `character` goes on to include `digit` and other printable ASCII characters, then it diverges even more from `letter`, which one can assume does not include the digit characters or any of the special (non-alphanumeric) characters.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] This definition appears overcomplicated because the concept of "optional whitespace" must be explicitly defined in BNF, but it is implicit in WSN.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] Even in this example, `text` is left undefined, but it is assumed to mean "`ASCII-character { ASCII-character }`".
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] (`EOL` is also left undefined.) Notice how the kludge `"<" rule-name ">"` has been used twice because `text` was not explicitly defined.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] One of the problems with BNF which this example illustrates is that by allowing both single-quote and double-quote characters to be used for a `literal`, there is an added potential for human error in attempting to create a machine-readable syntax.
[src:modula-2/wirth-syntax-notation] One of the concepts that migrated to later meta syntaxes was the idea that giving the user multiple choices made it harder to write parsers for grammars defined by the syntax, so computer languages in general have become more restrictive in how a *quoted-literal* is defined.
